1
00:05:23,447 --> 00:05:27,492
I can't hold her much longer.
She's taking on too much water.

2
00:05:27,742 --> 00:05:33,288
- What is going on back there?
- Keep your pants on, Murphy.

3
00:05:36,249 --> 00:05:40,044
We blew the starboard engine.
Port engine's way too hot.

4
00:05:40,293 --> 00:05:43,213
- Hold on.
- Shorten the tow or cut her loose.

5
00:05:43,463 --> 00:05:44,381
Epps...

6
00:05:44,631 --> 00:05:48,509
<i>... get off my damn tugboat.
We don't have much time.</i>

7
00:05:48,759 --> 00:05:54,472
<i>Move it, Epps. If she sinks,
she's taking us with her.</i>

8
00:06:00,226 --> 00:06:02,103
Got a punch in the port floater.

9
00:06:02,353 --> 00:06:05,272
<i>- Five minutes before she floods.
- Less than that!</i>

10
00:06:05,522 --> 00:06:07,983
Get back here.
We're cutting her loose.

11
00:06:08,233 --> 00:06:10,734
- Cut her loose.
- That's it. Get back here.

12
00:06:10,985 --> 00:06:12,695
Come on! You heard the man!

13
00:06:12,945 --> 00:06:18,866
Took us three months to get her off
the bottom. I will not lose her now!

14
00:06:19,116 --> 00:06:21,994
Goddamn it, Epps!
You can't fix everything!

15
00:06:22,244 --> 00:06:25,204
Christ!

16
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:35,504
<i>- For the last time, get back here!
- She's taking on too much water!</i>

17
00:06:36,380 --> 00:06:42,468
<i>Why do you always have to break
my balls? I said get back here!</i>

18
00:06:44,344 --> 00:06:51,184
<i>Do you want me to come down there
and kick your ass? Because I'll do it.</i>

19
00:06:55,353 --> 00:06:59,565
Here's to the best damn
salvage crew in the business!

20
00:06:59,815 --> 00:07:03,276
- We did it, guys!
- Yeah, look at that!

21
00:07:03,526 --> 00:07:07,863
All right. Nice work.

22
00:07:07,863 --> 00:07:12,909
- Here's to the fucking sea!
- To the sea.

23
00:07:16,495 --> 00:07:17,954
To a job well done.

24
00:07:18,205 --> 00:07:23,000
Mr. Murphy? I'm Jack Ferriman. I was
wondering if I could buy you a drink.

25
00:07:23,250 --> 00:07:26,836
He doesn't drink.

26
00:07:29,005 --> 00:07:32,049
Could I talk to you alone?

27
00:07:32,299 --> 00:07:37,595
You talk to me, you talk to my crew.
That's the way it is.

28
00:07:37,887 --> 00:07:42,349
I fly the Arctic Weather Patrol flights
out of Mackenzie Bay.

29
00:07:42,599 --> 00:07:48,103
Last month I was out in the middle
of the Strait when I came across this.

30
00:07:48,354 --> 00:07:51,773
Congratulations. You found a boat.

31
00:07:52,023 --> 00:07:55,275
In the middle of the ocean,
of all places.

32
00:07:55,526 --> 00:07:58,612
I tried for radio contact
and got nothing...

33
00:07:58,862 --> 00:08:01,823
...so I figured she had to be adrift.

34
00:08:02,073 --> 00:08:03,574
In the Bering Strait?

35
00:08:03,825 --> 00:08:07,160
That's miles from shipping lanes.
Did you alert the Coast Guard?

36
00:08:07,410 --> 00:08:11,372
It's international waters,
so they noted it and that's it.

37
00:08:11,622 --> 00:08:12,998
You get a name?

38
00:08:13,249 --> 00:08:17,585
No, I put it out of my head until
two days ago when I saw it again.

39
00:08:17,836 --> 00:08:21,171
What are we talking about?
What kind of tonnage?

40
00:08:21,421 --> 00:08:25,466
Big. Huge.
Could be military.

41
00:08:25,716 --> 00:08:29,344
Let's say that we're
a little bit interested.

42
00:08:29,594 --> 00:08:31,847
What's in it for you?

43
00:08:32,097 --> 00:08:35,850
I want 20% finder's fee,
whatever she's worth.

44
00:08:36,100 --> 00:08:41,980
- Have you told anyone else about this?
- Not a living soul.

45
00:08:43,021 --> 00:08:47,734
- Give us a minute, will you?
- Okay.

46
00:08:47,984 --> 00:08:50,653
So? What do you think, Murph?

47
00:08:50,903 --> 00:08:53,738
Who knows? Could be full of shit.

48
00:08:53,989 --> 00:08:58,200
I do know one thing. I've seen strange
things happen in the Strait.

49
00:08:58,450 --> 00:09:02,495
I know something else:
Sea gives you an opportunity, take it.

50
00:09:02,745 --> 00:09:07,708
That's at least a week out of our way.
We've been out for six months already.

51
00:09:07,958 --> 00:09:12,253
I got a fiancée waiting, remember?
I'm getting married in a month.

52
00:09:12,503 --> 00:09:16,631
Plan was to go back to Anchorage.
Starboard diesel needs an overhaul.

53
00:09:16,882 --> 00:09:21,219
- In our business, the only plan is:
- There is no plan.

54
00:09:21,469 --> 00:09:26,556
If you don't want to go, that's fine.
Let's tell him we'll get somebody else.

55
00:09:26,806 --> 00:09:32,895
Wait a minute. Let's not be hasty.
What's a ship like that worth?

56
00:09:33,145 --> 00:09:34,229
Who knows?

57
00:09:34,480 --> 00:09:39,066
Millions? Thousands? Could be nothing.
Depends on a lot of things.

58
00:09:39,317 --> 00:09:43,069
- Mainly, if we have the right to salvage.
- Pretty big "if".

59
00:09:43,320 --> 00:09:47,072
- What's the split?
- We split it even, six ways.

60
00:09:47,323 --> 00:09:50,784
- Even split?
- Beats me paying you overtime.

61
00:09:51,034 --> 00:09:53,870
I'm good.

62
00:09:54,120 --> 00:09:57,164
I'm in.

63
00:09:57,206 --> 00:10:00,291
Greer? What do you say?

64
00:10:00,541 --> 00:10:03,419
All right.

65
00:10:04,711 --> 00:10:09,673
Hey, Ferriman! Can you come over here?

66
00:10:10,090 --> 00:10:16,554
So this is the way it works.
10% instead of your 20% finder's fee.

67
00:10:19,348 --> 00:10:22,893
I can't let you take advantage of me
like that.

68
00:10:23,143 --> 00:10:27,480
That's the way it is.
Take it or leave it.

69
00:10:32,609 --> 00:10:36,362
Fine. But I go with you.

70
00:10:36,487 --> 00:10:38,696
Not on my boat, you don't.

71
00:10:38,947 --> 00:10:42,992
Think I'd tell you where a fortune
might be without insurance?

72
00:10:43,242 --> 00:10:46,620
There are five other boats
that would jump at this.

73
00:10:46,870 --> 00:10:51,415
I come with you.
So you take it or leave it.

74
00:11:22,356 --> 00:11:24,942
Things are dull!

75
00:11:27,277 --> 00:11:30,155
She'll love it. What do you think?

76
00:11:30,405 --> 00:11:34,825
Too much off the sides, but I can
come up with something she'll love.

77
00:11:35,117 --> 00:11:38,244
- Shave that yourself.
- Don't want to help me out?

78
00:11:38,494 --> 00:11:45,125
Who the fuck are you kidding? Everybody
knows you Navy boys take it up the ass.

79
00:12:02,972 --> 00:12:07,642
- Enjoying the ride, Jack?
- No, sir.

80
00:12:20,152 --> 00:12:23,572
Not the same as flying planes
over ice sheets, is it?

81
00:12:23,822 --> 00:12:27,116
- What's the appeal?
- I could ask you the same thing.

82
00:12:27,366 --> 00:12:31,912
What's a nice girl doing in a dump
like this instead of raising a family?

83
00:12:32,162 --> 00:12:35,748
I own a third of Murphy's operation.
I'm not that nice.

84
00:12:35,998 --> 00:12:40,001
And these monkeys are my family.

85
00:12:40,126 --> 00:12:43,545
<i>Santos to Murphy. Come in.</i>

86
00:12:46,090 --> 00:12:49,300
- Yeah?
- I think you should get up here.

87
00:12:49,550 --> 00:12:54,012
<i>- What is it?
- I think you should see this!</i>

88
00:12:55,180 --> 00:12:58,599
It was there a second ago!
Ten miles to the northwest.

89
00:12:58,849 --> 00:13:02,478
Would you turn off that fucking music?

90
00:13:02,727 --> 00:13:06,272
I'm telling you, there must be a glitch.
I saw it with my own eyes.

91
00:13:06,523 --> 00:13:11,777
- Glitch, my ass. There's nothing there.
- Give me a look at this.

92
00:13:12,276 --> 00:13:17,823
There it is! Right in front of you!
Tell me you don't see nothing.

93
00:13:18,073 --> 00:13:23,119
Do you see what I'm saying?
Do you see what I'm saying to you?

94
00:13:23,369 --> 00:13:29,916
<i>- Dodge, could you get on the bow light?
- All right, Murph.</i>

95
00:13:33,544 --> 00:13:37,755
- It's there, right?
- There's something there.

96
00:13:44,052 --> 00:13:47,888
Hey, Murph, what's up?

97
00:13:48,556 --> 00:13:51,808
<i>Vessel at position 7-5 north...</i>

98
00:13:52,058 --> 00:13:55,186
...this is "Arctic Warrior".

99
00:13:55,437 --> 00:13:58,147
<i>Come in.</i>

100
00:13:58,397 --> 00:14:04,110
This is tugboat "Arctic Warrior".
Do you read me?

101
00:14:04,485 --> 00:14:06,486
This is "Arctic Warrior".

102
00:14:06,737 --> 00:14:09,947
<i>Do you read me? Come in.</i>

103
00:14:29,088 --> 00:14:31,840
Shit!

104
00:14:57,360 --> 00:15:01,280
- Now do you believe me?
- Holy shit!

105
00:15:01,530 --> 00:15:06,618
An ocean liner?
Where did that come from?

106
00:15:13,498 --> 00:15:16,626
It's the "Antonia Graza".

107
00:15:16,876 --> 00:15:19,669
Jesus Christ.

108
00:15:19,920 --> 00:15:24,298
<i>This is civilian tugboat "Arctic Warrior".
Is there anyone aboard?</i>

109
00:15:24,548 --> 00:15:28,510
<i>This is civilian tugboat "Arctic Warrior".
Is there anyone aboard?</i>

110
00:15:28,760 --> 00:15:34,014
This is "Arctic Warrior".
Can you read us?

111
00:15:36,141 --> 00:15:40,770
- You know her, Murphy?
- Only in my dreams.

112
00:15:46,107 --> 00:15:49,777
Christ, she's beautiful.

113
00:15:50,027 --> 00:15:57,032
Italian liners couldn't compete for speed,
so they built floating art palaces instead.

114
00:15:57,282 --> 00:16:02,161
She was reported missing May 21,
1962, off the coast of Labrador.

115
00:16:02,412 --> 00:16:07,791
Funny thing is, there was no distress
signal. She just disappeared.

116
00:16:08,041 --> 00:16:14,714
Ever since, every captain's been looking
for her, hoping she hasn't gone down.

117
00:16:15,004 --> 00:16:17,882
- Do you know what this means?
- What?

118
00:16:18,133 --> 00:16:23,262
Under the law of the sea, she's ours.
Let's not keep a lady waiting.

119
00:16:23,512 --> 00:16:28,558
Santos, bring us alongside. Fire up
the crane. We got business to do.

120
00:16:28,808 --> 00:16:34,353
When we get onboard, stay together. We
don't know what kind of shape she's in.

121
00:16:34,603 --> 00:16:38,315
<i>- Take us up, Greer.
- Aye, aye, captain.</i>

122
00:16:38,566 --> 00:16:44,945
Hey, Murphy, please remember to keep
all channels open. Thank you.

123
00:16:47,698 --> 00:16:49,490
They won't let me go.

124
00:16:49,741 --> 00:16:53,869
Safety first.
That's why you go last, Jack.

125
00:16:54,119 --> 00:16:56,913
Can you sit down?
I'm trying to keep this steady.

126
00:16:57,164 --> 00:17:00,249
- I just want...
- Sit down! Get out of the way!

127
00:17:00,499 --> 00:17:03,293
Okay.

128
00:17:05,170 --> 00:17:09,006
She's had some battering over
the last 40 years, you can tell.

129
00:17:09,256 --> 00:17:13,134
<i>Stand by. Setting you down topside.</i>

130
00:17:14,260 --> 00:17:16,763
She's still a beaut.

131
00:17:17,013 --> 00:17:20,265
Unbelievable.

132
00:17:20,515 --> 00:17:23,225
You better stay alert. Watch your step.

133
00:17:23,476 --> 00:17:26,771
40 years of rust can turn
deck plates into quicksand.

134
00:17:27,020 --> 00:17:31,857
We'll make our way in at the fore,
then check the bridge. This way. Careful.

135
00:17:32,107 --> 00:17:37,820
<i>- Forward mast is history.
- Epps and Murphy, are they a couple?</i>

136
00:17:37,945 --> 00:17:42,699
Hell, no. She's like a daughter to him.
He'd be lost without her.

137
00:17:42,949 --> 00:17:46,786
Superstructure's in decent shape.
No sign of damage.

138
00:17:47,036 --> 00:17:53,875
<i>- Lifeboats are gone, stern to bow.
- Life preserver lockers are all empty.</i>

139
00:17:54,125 --> 00:17:56,710
Sure no survivors ever
turned up, Murph?

140
00:17:56,960 --> 00:18:01,756
Sure as we're walking on
the "Graza", Dodge. This way.

141
00:18:14,058 --> 00:18:16,976
Let's go.

142
00:18:25,066 --> 00:18:28,820
Jesus. She's no fiddler's green.

143
00:18:29,070 --> 00:18:32,114
<i>You're wrong, Munder. She's beautiful.</i>

144
00:18:32,364 --> 00:18:37,159
Whoever was on here originally
sure left in a hurry.

145
00:18:38,953 --> 00:18:41,496
Murphy, come in.

146
00:18:54,631 --> 00:18:58,634
Ladies and gentlemen,
welcome aboard. I'm Julie.

147
00:18:58,884 --> 00:19:03,388
I'll be your hostess this evening.

148
00:19:06,099 --> 00:19:09,393
Have some respect, okay?

149
00:19:16,482 --> 00:19:19,151
Check out all those champagne bottles.

150
00:19:19,401 --> 00:19:22,112
Looks like we missed
one hell of a party.

151
00:19:22,362 --> 00:19:26,532
- And one hell of a hangover.
- Shut up!

152
00:19:54,095 --> 00:19:55,930
- Shut up!
- Let's find the bridge.

153
00:19:56,180 --> 00:19:59,516
- Such a manly man.
- What?

154
00:19:59,767 --> 00:20:01,768
- You all right?
- Shut up!

155
00:20:02,018 --> 00:20:06,146
Come on, Mary, let's go.

156
00:20:09,983 --> 00:20:13,027
Murph, how many passengers
did she carry?

157
00:20:13,277 --> 00:20:17,864
Over 600. The créme de la créme
of society from all over Europe.

158
00:20:18,114 --> 00:20:19,866
Crew of 500 from Italy.

159
00:20:20,115 --> 00:20:24,286
Talk to me. How's everything going?

160
00:20:29,374 --> 00:20:33,794
Okay, good. This companionway
should get us to the bridge.

161
00:20:34,044 --> 00:20:38,047
Here, Epps, hold this.

162
00:20:54,810 --> 00:20:57,604
What's going on?

163
00:20:57,854 --> 00:21:00,606
- After you.
- No, after you.

164
00:21:00,856 --> 00:21:04,150
No, no. After me.

165
00:21:04,401 --> 00:21:07,529
Tough guy.

166
00:21:20,414 --> 00:21:23,541
Don't let go!

167
00:21:23,791 --> 00:21:28,044
- Pull! Pull!
- Please, Epps!

168
00:21:29,963 --> 00:21:32,007
Please, Epps, don't let go!

169
00:21:32,256 --> 00:21:36,385
- Give me your hand.
- Pull us up!

170
00:21:39,053 --> 00:21:42,681
Oh, God!

171
00:21:45,559 --> 00:21:50,146
I told you to watch your fucking step!

172
00:21:51,604 --> 00:21:55,608
- Oh, shit. Oh, Jesus.
- From now on, you let me lead. Okay?

173
00:21:55,859 --> 00:21:58,027
Let's go.

174
00:21:58,277 --> 00:22:04,115
- I think I just shit my pants.
- No, you always smell that way.

175
00:22:49,984 --> 00:22:53,780
Compass is dead.

176
00:22:57,783 --> 00:22:59,825
Helm's not responding, either.

177
00:23:00,076 --> 00:23:06,957
Fuel tanks are empty. She must've rode
on full throttle till she was bone-dry.

178
00:23:08,707 --> 00:23:11,835
Epps!

179
00:23:15,588 --> 00:23:20,926
I'm looking for the ship's log.
Let's get this documentation back...

180
00:23:21,176 --> 00:23:23,719
- Are you okay?
- Yeah.

181
00:23:23,970 --> 00:23:26,931
- You sure?
- Yeah.

182
00:23:27,181 --> 00:23:30,809
Let's get to it.

183
00:23:34,019 --> 00:23:37,313
Hey, check this out.

184
00:23:38,231 --> 00:23:43,026
- It's a watch. Congratulations, buddy.
- No. Look again, you moron.

185
00:23:43,277 --> 00:23:48,614
It's a digital watch. Do the math. They
didn't have digital watches in 1962.

186
00:23:48,906 --> 00:23:53,618
So we're not the first people to board
this ship. But she's ours now.

187
00:23:53,868 --> 00:23:59,832
Let's get some sleep, tow her at dawn.
Let's hope there's no more surprises.

188
00:24:00,082 --> 00:24:02,709
Amen to that.

189
00:24:06,503 --> 00:24:10,215
Oh, God.

190
00:24:13,426 --> 00:24:18,555
Epps, can I get some tea?

191
00:24:19,931 --> 00:24:24,101
Any sign of what might've happened?
How she got here?

192
00:24:24,351 --> 00:24:27,186
That's the $64 million question,
isn't it?

193
00:24:27,437 --> 00:24:30,314
Ever hear of a ship called
the "Marie Celeste"?

194
00:24:30,564 --> 00:24:35,443
Twin-masted brigantine out of
Charleston during the Civil War.

195
00:24:35,693 --> 00:24:38,946
She was bound for London
with a cargo of cotton.

196
00:24:39,196 --> 00:24:41,448
Thanks.

197
00:24:41,698 --> 00:24:46,118
Two months after she set sail, she was
sighted by fishermen off Tripoli.

198
00:24:46,368 --> 00:24:50,079
She was doing 12 knots an hour
in a stiff breeze.

199
00:24:50,330 --> 00:24:56,793
Something wasn't quite right. They
didn't know what so they went onboard.

200
00:24:57,044 --> 00:25:00,755
You know what they found?

201
00:25:02,381 --> 00:25:03,965
Nothing.

202
00:25:04,215 --> 00:25:08,677
No passengers. No crew. No captain.

203
00:25:08,928 --> 00:25:11,055
No sign of distress.

204
00:25:11,305 --> 00:25:17,518
59 days after the last log entry, it had
traveled 4500 miles across the ocean...

205
00:25:17,769 --> 00:25:25,441
...past the Rock of Gibraltar and into
the Mediterranean Sea at full sail.

206
00:25:25,483 --> 00:25:27,859
And nobody at the helm.

207
00:25:28,109 --> 00:25:32,405
- What do you make of that?
- A ghost ship.

208
00:25:32,780 --> 00:25:38,576
Hey, you smell that?
I smell bullshit.

209
00:25:40,203 --> 00:25:43,080
- Been on the sea a lot longer than you.
- I know.

210
00:25:43,330 --> 00:25:47,833
Seen things that
you can't even imagine.

211
00:25:48,084 --> 00:25:52,837
<i>Maritime history is full of
Marie Celestes.</i>

212
00:25:53,088 --> 00:25:55,674
So, what's our plan?

213
00:25:55,924 --> 00:25:59,677
I think we should do what we came
to do. Tie her up, tug her in.

214
00:25:59,927 --> 00:26:05,348
You think our little tug
will pull this entire ocean liner?

215
00:26:05,598 --> 00:26:07,516
Not with the problems we got.

216
00:26:07,766 --> 00:26:11,894
We could set her at anchor
and come back with two or three tugs.

217
00:26:12,144 --> 00:26:14,730
No, some Russian trawler
will come along.

218
00:26:14,981 --> 00:26:18,900
I've already looked for her anchors,
anyway. They're gone.

219
00:26:19,150 --> 00:26:22,069
- What do you think?
- Get the engines working...

220
00:26:22,319 --> 00:26:26,447
...it could take us two weeks
minimum to tow a vessel this size.

221
00:26:26,698 --> 00:26:32,536
For my share of what she's worth,
I'd drag her back to Anchorage myself.

222
00:26:42,669 --> 00:26:44,462
Don't let go!

223
00:26:44,712 --> 00:26:51,009
Help me! Don't let go!

224
00:26:51,217 --> 00:26:57,014
- Thought you might want a jacket.
- Thanks.

225
00:27:07,397 --> 00:27:08,772
Boy, do I miss that.

226
00:27:09,023 --> 00:27:14,527
You okay? You seem quiet
since you came back.

227
00:27:15,778 --> 00:27:20,240
I think I saw something
I couldn't possibly have seen.

228
00:27:20,490 --> 00:27:22,784
- Like what?
- No, it's crazy.

